    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-11T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-11T14:00:00-05:00" n="618"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d618">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6124: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-11T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 11, 1936—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>123. Your 186, April 7, 6 p.m., final paragraph. In view of (<hi rend="italic"
                        >a</hi>) the reported activities of Leith-Ross in connection with the
                    proposed <pb facs="0684" n="589" xml:id="pg_589"/> settlements of both
                    Tientsin–Pukow and Hukuang loans, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) the intimate
                    association of Leith-Ross with the British Treasury and Foreign Office, and (<hi
                        rend="italic">c</hi>) the considerations outlined in Department’s 115, April
                    5, 8 p.m., particularly ultimate and penultimate paragraphs of section 1
                    thereof, Department would be at a loss to understand a refusal, if made by the
                    Foreign Office on the score that this is purely a private business matter, to
                    offer to those British interests concerned with the Hukuang loan a suggestion
                    that sympathetic consideration be given to the views of the American
                    interests.</p>
                <p>Department suggests that Atherton, unless you perceive objection thereto, convey
                    discreetly and orally to the appropriate British officials the substance of the
                    foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
